begin{example}
\backslash
label{example4}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Krull's interesection theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset A$
\end_inset

 an ideal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M=\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By Artin-Rees, the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M\right)\cap Q^{k}M\right\} _{k\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is stable.
 Thus, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q\left(\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M\right) & =Q\left(\left(\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M\right)\cap Q^{k}M\right)\\
 & =\left(\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M\right)\cap Q^{k+1}M\\
 & =\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Nakayama's lemma, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M=\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We define Cauchy sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with respect to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

-adic topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

, is called a 
\series bold
Cauchy sequence 
\series default
if, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{i}-a_{j}\in\mathfrak{m}^{n}\mbox{ for all }i,j\geq m.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
complete local ring
\series default
 if every Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
